[2m─── src/state/prs_tests_pagination.rs:110-152 ───[0m
[93m[bug · medium][0m In `assert_stale_pages_discarded`, the test verifies that stale page data is not
appended but does not assert that `list_pending()` is cleared after the discard. The helper calls
`mark_pr_list_page_loading` to simulate an in-flight request, then delivers stale responses, but
never checks `!state.prs_state.list_pending()` afterward. I verified that
`PaginatedList::accept_page` does clear `pending = None` even when returning `AcceptOutcome::Stale`,
so the missing assertion covers a real behavioral gap that this test would otherwise miss. If the
implementation were changed to leave the pending flag set when discarding, the UI could remain in a
perpetual loading state despite no new data being accepted, and this test would still pass. Add
`assert!(!state.prs_state.list_pending());` after each stale response to verify the loading flag is
correctly cleared.



[2m─── src/state/prs_tests_pagination.rs:23-52 ───[0m
[94m[maintainability · low][0m In `load_first_page_and_navigate_to_end`, the test allocates a request ID
via `state.prs_state.list.next_request_id().map(...).unwrap_or(0)`, relying on the assumption that
`begin_pr_list_reload` has already consumed an ID. If the fixture were ever changed so
`begin_pr_list_reload` no longer consumes an ID (or the counter were reset), this fallback would
silently use `request_id = 0`. While the current `PaginatedList::next_request_id` starts from `0`
via `last_request_id: ListRequestId::default()` and `checked_next` cannot return `Err` on the very
first call, `unwrap_or(0)` would still mask unexpected state corruption or fixture drift. To make
the test more explicit and robust, replace the fallback with `expect("expected prior request id
consumption")` so that a broken assumption fails loudly instead of silently reusing `0`.
